Cell-density of Microcystis samples was estimated using a visual ﬂow cytometry (FCM) (Flowsight, Meck, USA), as described by Li et al. (2020, 2021)
                        . Cellular surface structures of high- and low-viability Microcystis were observed using a transmission electron microscope (TEM) (Hitachi H-7650, Japan) (Li et al., 2020
                        ). Meanwhile, organic matters absorbed on cellular surface of Microcystis were extracted, according to protocols by Tang et al. (2017), and organics concentration was determined via dissolved organic carbon (DOC) quantification. Before water matrix analyzes, high- and low-viability Microcystis samples of 10 mL were filtered through a 0.45 µm glass fiber membrane (Millipore, USA). DOC of extracellular organic matters (EOMs) was measured by persulfate wet oxidation technique (Shimadzu TOC-V WP). UV absorbance at 254 nm (UV254) of aromatic compounds was measured using a UV3600 Spectrophotometer (Shimadzu, Japan). Alkalinity was quantified using acid titration standard method with methyl orange (Urchem, China) and phenothalin (SCR, China).

Cell-viability of Microcystis did not change the fast-slow pattern of ozone decay (Fig. 1). However, rate constant of ozone fast decay (k

                              fast
                           ) was higher for low-viability Microcystis than that for high-viability Microcystis treated by equal concentrations of ozonation (Fig. 1), indicating that the decrease of cell-viability could promote ozone decay, in similar with chlorination found by Li et al. (2020)
                           . Previous studies noted that ozone decay could be accelerated by elevated organic matters and aromaticity (Hitzfeld et al., 2000
                           ; 
                           Rositano et al., 2001
                           ; 
                           Brooke et al., 2006
                           ; 
                           Onstad et al., 2007
                           ; 
                           Coral et al., 2013). This study certified that DOC concentration and UV254 of source waters dominated by low-viability Microcystis was much higher than that by high-viability Microcystis (P < 0.05) (
                           Fig. 5). Hence, compared to high-viability Microcystis, elevated organics and aromaticity were the main factors to facilitate the fast process of ozone decay for low-viability Microcystis.

This study found that ozonation could gain a higher cell inactivation for low-viability Microcystis than that for high-viability Microcystis, but their potential of extracellular microcystin control (Δk

                           toxin
                        ) became much lower, leading to an elevated microcystin risk. This study further elucidated that an increase of organic loads and alkalinity were responsible for these variations of ozonation process for high- and low-viability Microcystis, indicating that pre-oxidation might not be a proper option to treat Microcystis-laden source waters dominated by low-viability cells. However, in DWTPs, when organic loads and alkalinity was reduced by coagulation or filtration, inter- and post-ozonation might be a more appropriate option to achieve both of microcystin risk control and Microcystis inactivation, but more investigations should be conducted.
